To capture the stacktrace of the failed method in the `@DataProvider` without using try/catch, you can use the `ITestResult` object provided by TestNG. Here&#39;s an example implementation of the `captureFailures()` method in the `CommonTest` class:

```

    @Dataprovider
    class CommonTest {
        private static List&lt;Throwable&gt; failures = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    
        @AfterMethod
        public void afterMethod(ITestResult result) {
            if (result.getStatus() == ITestResult.FAILURE) {
                failures.add(result.getThrowable());
            }
        }
    
        @AfterClass
        public void captureFailures() {
            if (!failures.isEmpty()) {
                System.out.println(&quot;Failures captured in @DataProvider:&quot;);
                for (Throwable failure : failures) {
                    failure.printStackTrace();
                }
            }
        }
    }
    
    class TestClass extends CommonTest {
        @DataProvider
        public Object[][] sampleMethod() {
            CommonUtils.doSomething();
            return new Object[][]{{}};
        }
    }
    
    class CommonUtils {
        public static void doSomething() {
            throw new RuntimeException(&quot;Failed to do something&quot;);
        }
    }

```

In this implementation, we use an `ArrayList` to store any `Throwable` objects that are captured by the `afterMethod()` method. This method is called after each test method, including methods annotated with `@DataProvider`. If the test result is a failure, we add the `Throwable` object to the `failures` list.

In the `captureFailures()` method, we check if the `failures` list is not empty. If there are any failures, we print out the stacktrace of each `Throwable` object in the list.

Note that we have also made the `CommonTest` class abstract and extended it in the `TestClass` class. This is because we want to use the `afterMethod()` method in the `CommonTest` class to capture the failures in the `@DataProvider` method of the `TestClass`.

You are correct that if there are failures in the @DataProvider method, the @AfterMethod or @AfterClass methods may not be invoked, and therefore you may not be able to get the ITestResult object.
In this case, you can use a ITestContext object to store the exception that is thrown in the @DataProvider method, and then retrieve it in the @AfterMethod or @AfterClass method. Here&#39;s an example implementation:

        class CommonTest {
        @AfterMethod
        captureFailures(ITestResult result) {
            Throwable throwable = result.getThrowable();
            if (throwable != null) {
                // Log or handle the exception here
            }
        }
    
        @AfterClass
        captureFailures(ITestContext context) {
            Throwable throwable = context.getFailedTests().getAllResults().stream()
                    .map(ITestResult::getThrowable)
                    .filter(Objects::nonNull)
                    .findFirst()
                    .orElse(null);
            if (throwable != null) {
                // Log or handle the exception here
            }
        }
    }
    
    class TestClass {
        @DataProvider
        sampleMethod() {
            try {
                CommonUtils.doSomething();
            } catch (Throwable t) {
                throw new SkipException(&quot;Skipping test due to exception in data provider&quot;, t);
            }
        }
    }
    
    class CommonUtils {
        static void doSomething() {
            // Your code here
        }
    }

Note that this implementation assumes that you are using a testing framework that supports the ITestContext and SkipException objects, such as TestNG. If you are not using such a framework, you may need to modify the implementation accordingly.

